    ></light-box>
    <p-lede
      >Commissioned by former City Council President Darrell Clarke before his
      retirement, <em>Legacies: Our Neighbors Lead & Inspire</em>, honors three
      powerhouse community leaders who impacted the lives of thousands of
      community members in this North Philadelphia neighborhood.</p-lede
    >
    <p
      >Designed by Ernel Martinez and Keir Johnston of the collective
      <a
        href="https://amberartanddesign.com/"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        >Amber Art and Design</a
      >, the mural complements a
      <a
        href="https://www.publicartarchive.org/art/Staircases-and-Mountaintops-Ascending-Beyond-the-Dream/6f95f086"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        >pre-existing mural of Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr.</a
      >. on the facade of the recreation center named in his memory. The
      original mural was created by a founding member of the collective, Willis
      NOMO Humphrey, who passed away in 2018, assisted by mosaic artist Jonny
      Buss. The dedication of
      <em>Legacies: Our Neighbors Lead & Inspire</em> was a stirring event with
      heartfelt stories shared about the three honorees,
      <a
        href="https://www.phillytrib.com/obituaries/helen-brown-77-community-organizer-for-project-home/article_bacf858e-0606-5616-a012-ba05287122c1.html"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        >Helen Brown</a
      >,
      <a
        href="https://phila.legistar.com/LegislationDetail.aspx?ID=5146676&GUID=A3B85B6F-7B90-4AC0-A318-F73663920E89&Options=&Search="
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        >Harold “Malcolm” McCoy</a
      >, and
      <a
        href="https://www.inquirer.com/philly/obituaries/bruce-webb-obituary-record-store-owner-83-20171205.html"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        >Bruce Webb</a
      >. Artists Ernel Martinez and Keir Johnston were assisted by Mtukufu
      Mtumaini-El, Juan Carlos Valencia Michileno, and members of the Rec Crew.
      The Martin Luther King, Jr., Recreation Center is located at 22nd Street
      and Cecil B. Moore Avenue.</p
    >
